passages.text: First Take: 2Q25 print in line with expectations

First Take - in line: 2Q25 profit was \(+3\%\) y/y, in line with expectations. 2Q25 revenue and PPoP were \(+1\%\) /flat y/y, 2ppt/1ppt higher than JPMe (Table 1). AQ is stable but impairment charges are 5ppt higher than JPMe. ABC's profit growth is slightly higher than that of its Big 4 peers (ICBC \(+1\%\) y/y, CCB \(+2\%\) y/y, BOC \(+1\%\) y/y), but its share price has outperformed peers meaningfully in past month (ABC- H \(+1.35\%\) , MSCI China banks \(- 5\%\) ), thus the slight beat to peers is in line with expectations. Also, ABC's PPoP was flat y/y, the weakest among the Big 4 (CCB \(+14\%\) y/y, ICBC \(+7\%\) y/y, BOC \(+2\%\) y/y). Thus, we expect ABC's share price to underperform its Big 4 peers post the 2Q print.

- Strong fee growth drives non-NII growth: 2Q fee growth was \(32\%\) y/y (vs 1Q \(-4\%\) y/y); for a detailed breakdown by item on a semi-annual basis, please refer to Table 7. 
- Loan and deposit growth are robust: Loans and deposits grew by \(10\%\) and \(8\%\) y/y; loan growth was highest among the big 4 banks. Though this may lead to AQ concerns in the long run. 
- Asset quality remained stable: SML ratio -1bps h/h, NPL ratio flat q/q at \(1.28\%\) , NPL coverage ratio was largely flat q/q to \(295\%\) , the highest among the Big 4.

- NII \(-3\%\) y/y with NIM contracted 4bps q/q: NIM yoy contraction was 17bps y/y, the second highest among the Big 4 banks. Please see Table 4 for details. 
- CET 1 ratio declined by 12bps q/q to \(11.11\%\) : The lowest among the Big 4 banks. We expect ABC to receive a capital injection in 2026, and its share count dilution could be the highest among the Big 4 banks.
We expect muted consensus revisions.
- We expect a moderately negative share price reaction as 2Q PPoP growth lagged that of its Big 4 peers.
1288. HK, 1288 HK Price: HK\$5.25 29 Aug 2025 Price Target: HK\$6.10 PT End Date: 31 Dec 2026

Investment Thesis- Asset quality is improving: ABC has the highest NPL coverage ratio among the Big 4 banks, which we think provides it with more of a buffer for earnings in the future.- Capital positions are relatively weak among the Big 4 banks: ABC's CET 1 is lower than its Big 4 peers, while its RWA growth is higher.- ABC has the lowest overseas exposure among the Big 4 banks, so it is less affected by recession risks for overseas markets.

Our Dec- 26 PT of HK\$6.10 is based on our DDM calculations, using a cost of equity of \(11.25\%\) , a normalized ROE of \(9.3\%\) and a terminal date of 31 December 2027. We derive the valuation of the A- share first and then apply an H- share discount of \(20\%\) for ABC- H. Details are summarized in the valuation table below.
